    <h1>Historical Hacks</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A framework embedded in a full U.S. History course to help students think like historians, not just memorize events.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="content">

    <p>When I started developing Lumen's U.S. History course, I kept running into the same problem: most students think history means memorizing dates and facts, and a lot of courses end up reinforcing that idea even when they don't intend to. The skills historians actually use, things like analyzing primary sources, evaluating arguments, and understanding historical context, tend to go unaddressed.</p>

    <div class="section-eyebrow">What the Research Showed</div>

    <p>I did a lot of research before building this course because I wanted it to appropriately address common weaknesses in introductory history courses. I read the latest AHA publications, community college and other course syllabi, course design literature, and Indiana University's History Learning Project research on where students commonly get stuck. The Indiana research identified seven recurring "bottleneck" areas where intro history students consistently struggled: understanding the role of facts, interpreting primary sources, maintaining appropriate emotional distance, understanding the limits of historical actors' knowledge, identifying with people in another time and place, constructing and evaluating arguments, and linking details to broader context. These weren't fringe issues; thousands of students across the country struggled with the same things.</p>

    <p>The DFWI rates in U.S. History (D, F, Withdraw, or Incomplete) averaged 25% overall and 42% for Black students. As a gateway course, failing out of U.S. History can have serious repercussions on a student's future college success.</p>

    <div class="section-eyebrow">Building Historical Hacks Into the Course</div>

    <p>My solution was to build historical thinking directly into the course architecture. I designed Historical Hacks as short, dedicated sections at the end of each module that name a specific thinking skill, explain it clearly, connect it to that module's content, and give students a chance to practice it. The skills scaffold across the course, starting with foundational work like analyzing primary sources and building toward more complex skills like constructing historical arguments. The idea is that these skills contribute to student success and engagement within the course, but also prepare students for critical thinking they will need outside of the history classroom.</p>

    <div class="hacks-grid">
      <div class="hack-card">
        <div class="hack-module">Module 1</div>
        <div class="hack-name">Recounting History</div>
        <div class="hack-skill">Primary vs. secondary sources; history as interpretation, not fact</div>
      </div>
      <div class="hack-card">
        <div class="hack-module">Module 3</div>
        <div class="hack-name">Analyzing Primary Sources</div>
        <div class="hack-skill">HAPPY analysis: Historical context, Audience, Purpose, Point of View, whY</div>
      </div>
      <div class="hack-card">
        <div class="hack-module">Module 5</div>
        <div class="hack-name">Evaluating Sources</div>
        <div class="hack-skill">SIFT method: Stop, Investigate, Find better coverage, Trace claims</div>
      </div>
      <div class="hack-card">
        <div class="hack-module">Module 11</div>
        <div class="hack-name">Understanding Historical Actors</div>
        <div class="hack-skill">Analyzing motive and context; recognizing the bias of presentism</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section-eyebrow">Implementation and Iteration</div>

    <p>The first version of the Historical Hacks was well received by faculty and students. But a real limitation showed up quickly: the course platform didn't let instructors see student responses to the open-ended Hack activities. Students had no way to submit their thinking, and instructors had no way to know if the Hacks were being used. "Students don't do optional," so we needed to rethink how to deliver them.</p>

    <p>I've been working on the course again in 2026 with new plans to change the approach. There's now a streamlined student-facing version and a new set of instructor guide extensions that bring the application into class time, where an instructor can actually facilitate and respond to what students are doing. If the platform can't close the loop between student thinking and instructor awareness, the design has to.</p>

